iversion did not confuse a tracking system. It kept the first camera outside the cutout from seeing a direct movement toward Washington if that camera existed and if anyone later recovered it. One turn. One minute. No theater.\n\nEarly contractor traffic had begun filling the commercial roads. Box trucks backed into bakery docks. Utility vans waited at a wholesale electrical supplier. PCF-27 moved among them at the speed of a vehicle whose driver wanted to reach a job, not escape a manhunt.\n\nMarcus navigated from memory and a folded road map found in the van. He kept the route off the toll road and away from the most obvious federal approaches. He did not claim any road lacked cameras.\n\n“Arlington Boulevard,” he said. “Then Roosevelt if it is moving. We make the final decision before the river.”\n\n“Parking?” Julie asked.\n\n“Commercial loading lane west of the Fenwick block. Morning contractors use it before office restrictions begin. Known van, ordinary context.”\n\n“Plate readers?”\n\n“Possible at every garage and major intersection.”\n\n“Then no garage.”\n\n“We park on the street and accept the clock.”\n\nElias leaned forward. “How far from the service entrance?”\n\n“Two blocks if the loading lane is open. Three if it isn’t.”\n\n“Marcus cannot walk that.”\n\n“Marcus is not walking it,” Julie said.\n\nHe looked out the window. “I can see the rear approach from the van if we use the west end of the lane.”\n\n“And the radio?”\n\n“County, federal interop if they move the search into the District, and whatever the service set picks up. No private channel to you.”\n\nJulie nodded. “Fixed clock. Seven-ten.”\n\n“I know.”\n\nThe mounted service set broke into a regional traffic advisory and returned to law-enforcement traffic. Marcus turned up the van’s ordinary dashboard radio. A local news anchor repeated the Building Three fire, the stolen classified material, and Julie’s name. The language had changed.\n\nSuspected sabotage became suspected architecture of the Ar